            "post_value": "At Microsoft, I owned end-to-end relationships with enterprise partners like Databricks and SAP, ran proactive account cadences across 45+ resilience drills, maintained a consolidated backlog of partner requests, and translated recurring feedback patterns into prioritized roadmap features with engineering. I also built an AI-powered planning agent that cut planning cycle time by 39% and reduced manual reporting effort across the portfolio. That combination of senior stakeholder ownership, customer-to-product translation, and building lightweight tools to scale the work is exactly what this role calls for.\n\nWhat draws me to Probably Genetic specifically is the mission and the technical bet behind it. Using machine learning and at-home testing to find undiagnosed rare disease patients, then connecting them to trials and treatments, is one of the more meaningful applications of data I have come across. I want to be close to a problem that actually matters, and I find the intersection of biopharma partnerships and a real patient-facing data platform genuinely compelling. A lean team moving fast in bioinformatics and AI, backed by Khosla and Threshold, is exactly the kind of environment where the work I do has a direct, visible impact."
