            "len": 1404,
            "post_value": "At Microsoft, I spent two years as the bridge between Azure engineering and enterprise partners during live deployments, untangling integration dependencies and keeping things on track when complexity threatened to derail critical programs. One of those programs was tied to a $1.5B+ sovereign-cloud contract, and the work came down to coordination, trust, and crafting on-the-ground solutions fast. That experience maps directly to what a Forward Deployed Engineer at Promise does every day: show up in a customer environment, make the technology actually work, and protect the relationship in the process. I also built an internal AI agent that cut planning cycle time by 39% by translating bottlenecks I observed firsthand into product improvements, which is exactly the feedback loop Promise describes for this role.\n\nWhat draws me to Promise specifically is the problem space. Government and utility systems that handle assistance programs are notoriously rigid, and the people who suffer when they fail are the ones who can least afford it. Promise is doing something technically hard and genuinely important: modernizing those systems in a way that reaches hundreds of thousands of households, cuts approval times from weeks to hours, and treats people with dignity. That combination of civic impact and serious engineering challenge is rare, and it is exactly the kind of work I want to be doing."
          }
